SIMPLE: occlusion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Occlusion
<hw>Oc*clu"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Occlude</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of occluding, or the
state of being occluded.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Constriction and <qex>occlusion</qex> of the orifice.</q>
<rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The transient approximation of the
edges of a natural opening; imperforation.</def>
<rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Occlusion of gases</b></col> <fld>(Chem. &
Physics)</fld>, <cd>the phenomenon of absorbing gases, as exhibited by
platinum, palladium, iron, or charcoal; <as>thus, palladium absorbs, or
<ex>occludes</ex>, nearly a thousand times its own volume of hydrogen,
and in this case a chemical compound seems to be
formed</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Occrustate</ent>⟦br⟧
